[I]{custom-style="initial-joined"}[n Tolkien's work]{.smallcaps}, the Blue Mountains hold a rather unique border position: in the early times of the ancient mythology depicted in _The Silmarillion,_ they are perceived as the ultimate rocky barrier to the east of Beleriand.
The scarce texts referring to the lands beyond are relatively vague.
Conversely, at the time of _The Lord of the Rings,_ they constitute the last mountain range west of Eriador, bordering the coasts of sunken Ossiriand.
In both cases, the maps of these regions always stop at these mountains, providing us with only a very partial view of Middle-earth.
We will probably never truly know what Eriador looked like before the submersion of Beleriand: how its southern coasts were shaped, the courses of its many rivers, and where they flowed into the sea, among other details.
Nonetheless, the partial reconstruction we aim to undertake in this essay, by superimposing several of Tolkien's maps, may offer some elements for consideration.

Similarly, the only published map of the great island of Númenor 
does not specify its location in relation to the continent.
In that case too, the texts seem to lack detail, but closer examination, reveal new clues.

As we shall see, such geographical reconstructions raise almost as many questions as they seem to resolve, constantly questioning the nature and reliability of the texts and maps of Middle-earth, as they are presented to us for reading or viewing --- so that, far from unveiling all the mysteries, they evoke others that are just as intriguing.


## On Beleriand and Eriador[^lhundirien-2]

### Stitching the maps

To achieve a precise alignment between the maps of Beleriand in the First Age and Eriador in the Third Age, we nowadays have three sources available: (A) the second map of Beleriand[^lhundirien-3] that Christopher Tolkien used as a basis for the simplified map in _The Silmarillion;_ (B) the initial map of the lands east of the Ered Luin,[^lhundirien-4] which served as a draft for the one Christopher Tolkien created at his father's request for _The Lord of the Rings_ and contains some interesting details; and finally (C), the map of Third Age Eriador revised by Christopher Tolkien for the publication of _Unfinished Tales._

Scales of maps (A) and (C) are indicated. As for map (B), it has no explicit scale but, has a grid, twice the size of (A).
It is therefore possible to resize these three maps in order to superimpose them.
In addition, thanks to (C), we know the position of the island of Himling, the last remnant of the hill of Himring on (A).
On (B), we also find Tol Fuin, a large residual island that follows the mountainous contours of the woods of Taur-na-Fuin on (A).
These few common elements make it possible to check _a posteriori_ the adequacy of the stitching thus carried out.


![Scaling and stitching Tolkien's maps.](images/map-tolkien-overlaying.png){width="99%"}


### The Blue Mountains, a literary frontier

The three laconic verses given in the epigraph of this article constitute, to our knowledge, the only description that Tolkien gives us of the Ered Luin or Ered Lindon, the Blue Mountains "which are the borders of the lands of which these tales tell".[^lhundirien-5]
We know little more about their appearance; at most can we glean, elsewhere, their name in Old English, _Hǽwengebeorg,_[^lhundirien-6] and some other variants in Elvish, such as _Lhúndirien,_ the "Blue Towers".[^lhundirien-7]


### The Gulf of Lhûn, where mountains crumbled

On our reconstructed map, the Bay of Balar appears roughly at the same latitude as the Gulf of Lhûn.
During the submersion of Beleriand, the Blue Mountains therefore collapsed and separated at the point where the land between the mountain range and the sea was the narrowest and lowest: the impact following the tidal wave was more violent there.


