### Amon Ereb, a preserved hill

On (B), a wavy line runs along the coast.
At the bottom of square J3, a small circle borders it, which surprises Christopher Tolkien:[^ereb-8]

> I cannot explain the wavy line that extends roughly parallel to the coast from H4 to K3.

He adds in a note:[^ereb-9]

> [In my 1943 map] neither the inner wavy line nor the small circular area are present.

However, if we transpose the distance between the island of Himling and this circle on the map of Beleriand, it coincides exactly with the hill of Amon Ereb.
There is little doubt that Tolkien first drew a coastline where Amon Ereb was still an island, but changed his mind and moved the coastline as we know it.
This part of Lindon remains relatively preserved, in line with texts affirming that the land where Beren and Lúthien lived was not submerged along with the rest of Beleriand.

