### Mount Dolmed, an unexpected vestige

Dolmed was an important mountain in the Ered Luin.
The Houses of the Dwarves, Tumunzahar (Nogrod) and Gabilgathol (Belegost), were not far from it.
In _The Complete Guide to Middle-earth_, Robert Foster writes:[^dolmed-10]

> Dolmed was probably destroyed at the breaking of Beleriand.

However, if we look more closely at map (C), we notice, just above the southernmost forest of Forlindon, a mountain standing a little apart from the others, vaguely at the height of Lake Nenuial.
It is enough for us to consult our reconstructed map to see that this mountain, which also corresponds to a schematized excrescence on (B), exactly superimposes on Mount Dolmed of (A).

![Mount Dolmed found back on map (C).](images/map-dolmed-rediscovered.png){width="99%"}

The proximity of the ancient homes of the Dwarves --- and therefore of
Mount Dolmed --- with Lake Nenuial is confirmed by _Unfinished
Tales_:[^dolmed-11]

> There were and always remained some Dwarves on the eastern side of Ered Lindon, where the very ancient mansions of Nogrod and Belegost had been -- not far from Nenuial

Thus, this mountain, slightly inland, seems to be Mount Dolmed, still
present in the Third Age. But why does Foster claim that the mountain
was destroyed? It is probably a somewhat hasty deduction on his part,
inspired by the following passage from _The Lord of the Rings_:[^dolmed-12]

> After the end of the first age [...], the ancient cities of Nogrod and Belegost in the Blue Mountains were ruined at the breaking of Thangorodrim

Most commentators seem to have interpreted _ruined_ as denoting a complete destruction, like Robert Foster with his "destroyed" Mount Dolmed.
The French translation of this passage also retains, without further ado, that "_les Montagnes Bleues furent détruites,_ the Blue Mountains were destroyed".

The passage from _Unfinished Tales_ quoted above, however, seems to affirm the opposite, testifying to a continued presence of the Dwarves in this region.
The annals in the appendix to _The Lord of the Rings_ probably go in the same direction:[^dolmed-13]

> c[irca] 40 Many Dwarves leaving their old cities in Ered Luin go to Moria and swell its number.

If the Dwarves took about forty years to migrate to Khazad-dûm after the submersion of Beleriand, it is probably because their homes still existed --- and _a fortiori_ Mount Dolmed too.
It is probably necessary to understand _ruined_ in a less categorical sense: Nogrod and Belegost were not only strongholds, but also the site of intense trade with the Elves.
After the submersion of Beleriand, the two cities become totally unsuitable and lose all their appeal: probably ruined on an economic level or, at least, _devastated_ after the upheavals suffered by the continent, but also by the central portion of the Blue Mountains --- now crossed by the Gulf of Lhûn but where the Dwarves must have had other mining installations (see _infra_).

In conclusion, despite a certain ambiguity of the texts as to the state of the cities of Nogrod and Belegost and the reasons for their progressive abandonment, the study of the maps seems to us to clearly demonstrate that Mount Dolmed survived the destruction.
For good measure, we could also presume that Mount Rerir, another notable peak north of the range, could also still exist, although it is less obvious to identify on the maps considered.

