## On the Houses of the Dwarves

### Concerning the location of Nogrod and Belegost

On the map of Beleriand drawn by Fonstad[^dwarves-cities-14] in _The Atlas of Middle-earth,_ Mount Dolmed is located on the parallel K, which also passes, on her map of Eriador,[^dwarves-cities-15] through the Gulf of Lhûn.
Fonstad, probably taking _The Complete Guide of Middle-earth_ as a reference, is then comforted in her idea:[^dwarves-cities-16]

> Lindon was the only portion of Beleriand that survided as part of the mainland, although Mount Dolmed and Rerir were both absent.

But if we examine Fonstad's maps, we discover an error of about 112 miles (or, roughly, some 180 km) in her recollage between Beleriand and Eriador.
Indeed, on her map of Beleriand, Himring is placed between lines I and J, while on her map of Eriador, the islet of Himling is between lines H and I.


![An erroneous stitching\
in Karen W. Fonstad's _Atlas of Middle-earth._](images/map-detail-fonstad-error.png){width="99%"}


This small mistake can only mislead Fonstad.
As we have seen, Dolmed is much higher than the Gulf of Lhûn, in a region little affected by the submersion of Beleriand.
Fonstad thus misses her discovery on the map of _The Lord of the Rings,_ just as she misses the alignment of the Bay of Balar and the Gulf of Lhûn.
But the consequences of this slight error of longitude go even further: Fonstad places the city of Belegost (Gabilgathol)[^dwarves-cities-17] far south of Mount Dolmed --- more precisely about 100 miles south of Nogrod.
This is entirely contradictory with _The Silmarillion_:[^dwarves-cities-18]

> To the north of the great height of Mount Dolmed was Gabilgathol, which the Elves interpreted in their tongue Belegost, that is Mickleburg; and southward was delved Tumunzahar, by the Elves named Nogrod, the Hollow­bold.

If Nogrod, on Fonstad's map, seems to be located on the southern slope of Mount Dolmed, Belegost is found to the south and no longer to the north of the mountain.


![Location of Belegost according to Karen W. Fonstad.](images/map-detail-fonstad-belegost.png){width="60%"}


There is certainly an unspoken desire to follow map (B), which indeed shows Belegost in the southern part of the Blue Mountains south of the Gulf of Lhûn (see diagram _supra_).
Indeed, Fonstad's position for Belegost seems to coincide exactly with that given by this map.
A little further on, we can also read:[^dwarves-cities-19]

> The Dwarf-city of Nogrod probably collapsed when the Blue Mountains broke apart. The Dwarves who escaped the ruin moved to lesser delvings --- especially in the south where Belegost apparently survived.

However, if we correct Fonstad's 112-mile error, Belegost should be much further south, outside the map of Beleriand that she has redrawn...
In our opinion, Fonstad should have followed the texts and not the single map showing this peculiarity (besides a copy of 1943).
Mentioning the difficulty would have been necessary, as Tolkien probably did not act without reason.
Why would he have tried to place Belegost there?
To find a trace of it, we perhaps have to go back to the first map of Beleriand[^dwarves-cities-20] sketched by Tolkien.
The cities are both indicated to the south, off the map.
If we follow Christopher Tolkien's commentary:[^dwarves-cities-21]

> The line of the road goes off the map in the south-east corner, with the direction: 'Southward in East feet of Blue Mountains are Belegost and Nogrod.'

In this early conception, Dolmed was the mountain through which the Dwarf-road to Beleriand passed, but their dwellings were both located much further, in the south of the regions of Beleriand shown on the map.

Tolkien never completely rejected his writings and sometimes returned years later to an old conception.
By indicating Belegost to the south of the Ered Luin, he probably formulated a simple working hypothesis, as for Amon Ereb, which we have mentioned above: the revision notes of _The Silmarillion_ after the publication of _The Lord of the Rings_ are quite confusing about the position of Belegost, which seems to have been considered, at least temporarily, further south.[^dwarves-cities-22]
By revisiting this previously abandoned position, Tolkien distances Belegost and Nogrod, perhaps thinking that two major commercial cities may be overly proximate...
But here we enter the realm of speculation.

The subject is intricate.
Even if Tolkien did intend to revise the position of Belegost, the texts do not reflect this, and any approach can only be fragmentary.
The only certainty we can have is that the Blue Mountains were entirely inhabited by the Dwarves and that there must have been a large number of mining installations, if not secondary dwellings.
This is the case in the northern regions, where King Arvedui found refuge:[^dwarves-cities-23]

> For a while Arvedui hid in the tunnels of old dwarf-mines near the far end of the Mountains, but he was driven at last by hunger to seek the help of the Lossoth, the Snowmen of Forochel.

As in the south, in these halls where Thorin and his companions resided during their exile:[^dwarves-cities-24]

> Dwarves dwelt, and still dwell, in the east side of the Blue Mountains, especially in those parts south of the Gulf of Lune, where they have mines that are still in use. For this reason they were accustomed to pass east along the Great Road.

This last quote could well be the end of the story.
It clearly attests to the existence of mining operations and dwellings in the southern part of the Ered Luin and, obviously, it is not Belegost.[^dwarves-cities-25]
If we want to go a little further, we must note another apparently contradictory quote.
In the chronology in Appendix A of _The Lord of the Rings_, the location indicated for the settlement of Thorin and his father in the Blue Mountains[^dwarves-cities-26] is consistent with the passage given just above:

> Thráin and his son Thorin wander westwards. They settle in the South of Ered Luin beyond the Shire.

However, the account by Gandalf of his meeting with Thorin in _Unfinished Tales_ gives a very different location:[^dwarves-cities-27]

> For just as I was nearing Bree I was overtaken by Thorin Oakenshield, who lived then in exile beyond the north western borders of the Shire. [...] So I went with him to his halls in the Blue Mountains.

The Shire being located roughly at the level of the Gulf of Lhûn, this passage is hardly compatible with the others, unless we assume that Thorin, always in exile and therefore without any real fixed attachment, had meanwhile settled in other dwellings of his people, located this time north of the gulf.


