### Concerning the other mansions of the Dwarves

To complete our study, we must mention an even later text, where we learn the names of the seven Houses of the Dwarves:[^mansions-28]

> [The awakening place of the ancestors of the Firebeards and the Broadbeams] had been in the north of the Ered Lindon, the great eastern walls of which the Blue Mountains of the second and later ages were the remnant; [that of the ancestors of the
Longbeards] had been Mount Gundabad.

The Fathers of the Dwaves are grouped in pairs, except for Durin, and Christopher Tolkien remarks in a note that the first two families are very likely those of Belegost and Nogrod.
The text continues by stating that the Dwarves did not like to move away from their place of origin (the Longbeards were forced to do so after the invasion of Gundabad by the Orcs).
Independently of the validity of this version of the legend, this passage would seem to confirm the proximity of Belegost and Nogrod.
The text then mentions the other Houses of the Dwarves:[^mansions-29]

> The other two [awakening] places were eastward, at distances as great or greater than that between the Blue Mountains and Gundabad.

Although imprecise, this text suggests a minimum distance between the awakening sites of the Dwarves.
Visualizing this distance on a map might provide valuable insights.

Defined in this manner, the sphere of influence of Durin's Folk encompasses, at the very least, the Iron Hills, where it is known that Dwarves from this House indeed settled.
However, the White Mountains (to the south) and the Ephel Duath (around Mordor) do not belong to this territory. Nevertheless, the astonishment and wonder expressed by Gimli when he discovers the glittering caves of Aglarond in the White Mountains reveal that these were unknown to the Dwarves.
Following the War of the Ring, Gimli establishes his own colony there, thus expanding the influence area of his people towards the south.
As for the mountains of the infamous Mordor, it seems highly unlikely that the Dwarves could ever have settled there.

The hills of Dorwinion, near the Sea of Rhûn, appear to be beyond the sphere of influence of Durin's Folk.
They might have been colonized by other Houses, even though their altitude, probably modest, doesn't seem plausible as an awakening site --- at best, perhaps, as a potential trading location between the eastern mansions and House of Durin.


![Minimum distance between the Mansions of the Dwarves.[^mansions-30]](images/map-dwarves-distance.png){width="99%"}


The only other known mountains farther east are the red Orocarni,[^mansions-31] beyond the shores of the Sea of Helcar,[^mansions-32] but we cannot accurately position them on a map.
Therefore, we cannot provide further information about the last two Mansions of the Dwarves, except that they contributed troops during the War between the Dwarves and Orcs in the Third Age:[^mansions-33]

> Thráin at once sent messengers bearing the tale, north, east, and west; but it was three years before the Dwarves had mustered their strength.
> Durin's Folk gathered all their host, and they were joined by great forces sent from the Houses of other Fathers; for this dishonour to the heir of the Eldest of their race filled them with wrath.


